==English==
===Expression===
'''[[stick]]s and [[stone]]s'''

# [[primitive]] or [[makeshift]] weaponry
#*'''20C,''' Albert Einstein, letter to Harry S. Truman, as quoted by Alex Johnson in ''The culture of Einstein'' (2005)
#*:I do not know with what weapons World War III will be fought, but World War IV will be fought with '''sticks and stones'''.
#*'''2001,''' Edward Gibbon, ''The History of the Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire''
#*:The multitude, armed with '''sticks and stones''', drove them back into the Capitol.
#*'''2002,''' Vladimir A. Kozlov, ''Mass Uprisings in the USSR: Protest and Rebellion in the Post-Stalin Years''
#*:On July 1 a group of Soviet and party activists tried to “establish contact with the people who were in the convent,” but were beaten back with '''sticks and stones'''.
# Evocative of the expression ''"sticks and stones may'' (or ''will'') ''break my bones, but words'' (or ''names'') ''will never hurt'' (or ''harm'') ''me"''.
#*'''1957,''' Brendan Gill, ''The Day Money Stopped''
#*:‘You cheap dead-beat son of a bitch.’ ‘'''Sticks and stones'''.’
#*'''1993,''' ''[[w:The Independent|The Independent]]'', 15 May
#*:He has come through the worst and now presents a stoical ‘'''sticks and stones'''’ front to his detractors.
#*'''2003,''' ''[[w:Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl|Pirates of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Pearl]]'' (film)
#*:Elizabeth Swann: You're despicable!
#*:Jack Sparrow: '''Sticks and stones''', love.
